The paper focuses on using computational linguistic techniques to analyze group communication and detect sociocognitive roles in multiparty interactions. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Natural Language Processing (cs.CL) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of clustering and linear mixed-effects modeling, which are common techniques in the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also touches on the social and human aspects of collaborative learning, which could place it in the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. The paper's focus on analyzing large datasets could also place it in the Cybernetics (cs.CY) and Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-categories.
